A Seismologically Consistent Surface Rupture Length Model for Unbounded and Width-Limited Events

Grigorios Lavrentiadis, UCLA & Caltech

Yongfei Wang, SCEC

Norman A. Abrahamson, UC Berkeley

Yousef Bozorgnia, UCLA

Christine Goulet, SCEC

2022-07-30

Introduction

This study presents a new \(SRL\) model with a defensible physical scaling for unbounded and width-limited ruptures.

Study Objectives

  • Scaling consistent with seismological theory
  • Captures scaling for width-limited ruptures

Load Data

The empirical data that are used in model development include the FDHI (Sarmiento et al. 2021), Wells and Coppersmith (1994), and Baize et al. (2020) datasets. The surface rupture lengths (\(SRL\)) of the events in FDHI dataset are computed based on the Event Coordinate System (ECS), while the \(SRL\) in Wells and Coppersmith (1994) and Baize et al. (2020) are reported directly. Additionally, the results of the Wang and Goulet (2021) dynamic rupture simulations are used to derive the rupture width model.

#read srl flatfiles

Outliers

The following events were excluded from the regression dataset:

  • Events less than \(\mathbf{M}~5\)
  • 1892 Laguna Salada: it was occurred in 1892 but mapped in the 2010s. Magnitude is estimated.
  • 1978 IzuOshima: surface is incomplete, rupture probably extended offshore to southeast; epicenter is offshore ~17 km
  • 1993 Killari: it occurred in a stable continental region; probably a lot of deformation accommodated via folding/warping that was unmapped

Model Development

Rupture Width Modeling Based on SCEC Simulations

The SCEC simulations were used to develop a Magnitude - Rupture width model for unbounded and width-limited ruptures. Two models were evaluated: (i) a linear model between \(W - \mathbf{M}\), hereafter denoted as model w0, and (ii) a model with a scaling break at \(W_{lim}\), hereafter denoted as model w1

The functional form for model_w0 is: \[\begin{equation} \log(W) = \mathbf(M) + \epsilon_W \end{equation}\]

The functional form for model_w1 is: \[\begin{equation} log(W) = \min(\beta_1 + \beta_2 \mathbf{M}, \log(W_{lim})) + \epsilon_W \end{equation}\]

## Regression formulas
form_model_w0 <- log10(wef) ~ 1 + magnitude
form_model_w1 <- log10(wef) ~ 1 + magnitude

## Regression
fit_model_w0 <- lm(form_model_w0, data=df_SCEC_srl)
fit_model_w1 <- lm(form_model_w1, data=subset(df_SCEC_srl, !flag_wlim))

The \(W - \mathbf{M}\) model summary is presented below. model w1 has a higher log likelihood and lower Akaike information criterion.

SRL Model Derivation

This section presents the deviation of the \(SRL\sim\mathbf{M}\) functional form. The Seismic Moment (\(M_0\)) is defined as:

\[\begin{equation} M_0 = \mu~\bar{D}~L~W \end{equation}\]

where \(\mu\) is the stiffness of the crust, \(\bar{D}\) is the average slip on the rupture, \(L\) is the length of the rupture, and \(W\) is width of the rupture. Taking the log of the previous equation and substituting the definition of the Moment Magnitude (\(\mathbf{M}=0.667\) \(\log(M)\) \(- 10.7\)) we get:

\[\begin{equation} \mathbf{M} = \frac{2}{3}\log(\mu) + \frac{2}{3}\log(\bar{D}) + \frac{2}{3}\log(L) + \frac{2}{3}\log(W) - 10.7 \end{equation}\]

Since stiffness of the crust (\(\mu\)) is constant, the equation simplifies to:

\[\begin{equation} \mathbf{M} = \frac{2}{3}\log(\bar{D}) + \frac{2}{3}\log(L) + \frac{2}{3}\log(W) + c \end{equation}\]

where \(c\) is used to denote an arbitrary constant.

Two commonly used scaling models for the average displacements found in the literature include the \(\sqrt{A}\) model, hereafter called model 1, and the \(W\) model, hereafter called model 2 (Scholz, 1982; Romanowicz, 1992; Romanowicz and Rundle, 1993; Romanowicz, 1994; Scholz, 1994; Bodin and Brune, 1996; Pegler and Das, 1996; Scholz, 1997, 1998; Hanks and Bakun, 2002; Leonard, 2010). In model 1, the average displacement is assumed to scale linearly with the square root of the rupture area:

\[\begin{equation} \bar{D} = c \sqrt{A} = c \sqrt{L~W} \end{equation}\]

while in model 2, the average displacement is assumed to scale linearly with the width of the rupture:

\[\begin{equation} \bar{D} = c W \end{equation}\]

Both options will be evaluated against the empirical data to decide which is best. Using model 1 the \(\mathbf{M}\) scaling relationship becomes: \[\begin{equation} \mathbf{M} = \log(L) + \log(W) + c \end{equation}\] Similarly, with model 2 the \(\mathbf{M}\) scaling relationship becomes: \[\begin{equation} \mathbf{M} = \frac{2}{3}\log(L) + \frac{4}{3}\log(W) + c \end{equation}\]

Substituting model w1 from the SCEC rupture simulations, for model 1 we get: \[\begin{equation} \mathbf{M} = \log(L) + \min(\beta_1 + \beta_2 \mathbf{M}, \log(W_{lim})) + c \end{equation}\] and for model 2 we get: \[\begin{equation} \mathbf{M} = \frac{2}{3}\log(L) + \frac{4}{3} \min(\beta_1 + \beta_2 \mathbf{M}, \log(W_{lim})) + c \end{equation}\]

Consistent with Leonard (2010), assuming the surface to sub-surface rupture length scaling is of the form \(\log(SRL) = \alpha \log(L) + \beta\), substituting it to the previous equations, condensing the constants, and solving for \(\log(SRL)\), for model 1 we get: \[\begin{equation} \log(SRL) = c_1 \left( \mathbf{M} - \min(\beta_1 + \beta_2 \mathbf{M}, \log(W_{lim})) \right) + c = c_1 \alpha X_1 + c \end{equation}\] and for model 2 we get: \[\begin{equation} \log(SRL) = c_1 \frac{3}{2} \left( \mathbf{M} - 2 \min(\beta_1 + \beta_2 \mathbf{M}, \log(W_{lim})) \right) + c = c_1 X_2 + c \end{equation}\] both of which can be expressed as linear models with, \(X_1 = \mathbf{M} - \min(\beta_1 + \beta_2 \mathbf{M}, \log(W_{lim})\), and \(X_2 = \frac{3}{2} \mathbf{M} - 2 \min(\beta_1 + \beta_2 \mathbf{M}, \log(W_{lim}))\).

The effect of the style of faulting is also considered through the use of additive terms to account for differences in the static stress drop. The static stress drop is defined as: \[\begin{equation} \Delta \sigma = C \mu \frac{\bar{D}}{L_C} \end{equation}\] thus, in log scale, a shift in the stress drop will be accompanied by a linear shift in the average displacement (\(\log(\bar{D}) = \log(\Delta \sigma) + const\)), which, in turn, will shift the intercept of the \(SLR \sim \mathbf{M}\) models
Two modeling approaches were evaluated: (i) a common additive term for dip-slip events (\(F_D\)), and (ii) separate additive terms for Normal and Reverse faults (\(F_N\) and \(F_R\)). The style of faulting dependence introduced through \(F_D\), \(F_N\), and \(F_R\) acts in addition to the style of faulting dependence introduced by the different dip angles between the different styles of faulting.

The final regression relationship for model 1 is: \[\begin{equation} \log(SRL) = c_1 X_1 + c_2 F_D + c_3 \end{equation}\] the final regression relationship for model 2 is: \[\begin{equation} \log(SRL) = c_1 X_2 + c_2 F_D + c_3 \end{equation}\] and the final regression for separate additive terms with \(D \sim \sqrt{A}\) scaling, hereafter denoted as model 1alt is: \[\begin{equation} \log(SRL) = c_1 X_1 + c_2 F_N + c_3 F_R + c_4 \end{equation}\] Lastly a Wells and Coppersmith type model was also evaluated, hereafter referred as model 0, to investigate the impact of width limited ruptures on state of practice models. \[\begin{equation} \log(SRL) = c_1 \mathbf{M} + c_2 F_D + c_3 \end{equation}\]

The coefficients of the previous equations are estimated through a maximum likelihood regression.

Surface Rupture Length Modeling Based on Empirical Data

The Four candidate models were evaluated in predicting \(SRL\) as a function of \(\mathbf{M}\) which are summarized in Table 4.

Table 4. Candiate Regression Models
Name Functional Form Description
model 0 \(\log(SLR)\sim 1 + \mathbf{M} + F_D\) W&C 94 type model
model 1 \(\log(SLR)\sim1 + X_1 + F_D\) \(\bar{D} \sim \sqrt{A}\) type model with \(F_D\) addative term
model 2 \(\log(SLR)\sim 11+X_2 + F_D\) \(\bar{D} \sim {W}\) type model with \(F_D\) addative term
model 1 alt \(\log(SLR)\sim1 + X_1 + F_N+F_R\) \(\bar{D} \sim \sqrt{A}\) type model with \(F_N\) & \(F_R\) addative terms

The next part shows the definition of the regression functional forms and model fit.

# Rupture Width Modeling
#rupture width coefficients
c1_rw <- df_SCEC_model_width_mag_coeffs['model_w1','intrcp']
c2_rw <- df_SCEC_model_width_mag_coeffs['model_w1','M']
#compute rupture widths 
df_FDHI_srl$rup_width_unbnd <- 10^(c1_rw + c2_rw*df_FDHI_srl$magnitude)
df_FDHI_srl$rup_width <- pmin(df_FDHI_srl$rup_width_unbnd, df_FDHI_srl$seis_width)

#identify width limited events
df_FDHI_srl$flag_wlim <- FALSE
df_FDHI_srl[df_FDHI_srl$rup_width >= df_FDHI_srl$seis_width-1,'flag_wlim'] <- TRUE 


# SRL Modeling
#scaling parameters
df_FDHI_srl$x1 <-     df_FDHI_srl$magnitude -   log10(df_FDHI_srl$rup_width)
df_FDHI_srl$x2 <- 3/2*df_FDHI_srl$magnitude - 2*log10(df_FDHI_srl$rup_width)
#standard deviation weights
width_scl <- 0.1
sig_scl   <- 2
df_FDHI_srl$reg_wt <- ( 1 + (sig_scl-1) * sigmoid( 2.197225 * (log10(df_FDHI_srl$rup_width_unbnd)-log10(df_FDHI_srl$seis_width))/ width_scl ) )^2

## Regression formulas
form_model_srl0m     <- log10(event_len) ~ 1 + magnitude + FD
form_model_srl1m     <- log10(event_len) ~ 1 + x1 + FD
form_model_srl2m     <- log10(event_len) ~ 1 + x2 + FD
form_model_srl1m_alt <- log10(event_len) ~ 1 + x1 + FN + FR

## Regression
fit_model_srl0m     <- lm(form_model_srl0m,     data=df_FDHI_srl)
fit_model_srl1m     <- lm(form_model_srl1m,     data=df_FDHI_srl, weights=reg_wt)
fit_model_srl2m     <- lm(form_model_srl2m,     data=df_FDHI_srl, weights=reg_wt)
fit_model_srl1m_alt <- lm(form_model_srl1m_alt, data=df_FDHI_srl, weights=reg_wt)

The printout below summarizes the log-likelihood and Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) for the different candidate models, while Table 5 summarizes the estimated coefficients. Between the base models (Model 0 to 2), Model 1 and 2 have similar performance and Model 0 is the worst. Model 0 does not consider the finite thickness of the crust, showcasing the limitations of a purely empirical model. Both Model 1 and 2 have a break in the magnitude scaling when the width of the rupture reaches the width of the crust, allowing them to better fit the data. Model 1 (\(\bar{D} \sim \sqrt{A}\) type scaling) performs a marginally better than Model 2 (\(\bar{D} \sim W\) type scaling); however the main reason Model 1 is preferred is because of the value of the estimated slope coefficient (\(c_2\)). From seismological theory, both Model 1 and Model 2 should have unit slopes with respect to \(X_1\) and \(X_2\) terms if the subsurface rupture length was the response variable. Leonard (2010) proposed \(\log(SRL) = 1.1 \log(L) - 0.275\) for the scaling between \(SRL\) and \(L\). This results in a theoretical slope of \(0.91\), which is much closer to the \(X_1\) slope in model 1, which is \(0.93\), than to the \(X_2\) slope, which is \(0.70\).

A rupture width transition parameter \(\delta_W\) is defined as \(\delta_W = \log_{10}(W_{unb}) - \log_{10}(W_{lim})\); \(W_{unb}\) is the theoretical rupture width for an infinite thickness crust estimated from the first leg of model w1 (\(\log_{10}(W_{unb}) = \beta_1 \mathbf{M} + \beta_2\)). A negative value of \(\delta_W\) corresponds to a unbounded rupture, whereas a positive corresponds to a width limited rupture. Figure 12 shows the model 1 regression residuals versus \(\delta_W\). The solid black lines correspond to the rupture width transition dependent standard deviation.

Comparison With Existing Models

Figure 14 compares the preferred model with existing \(SLR\) relationships. WC94 All and WC94 SS correspond to the Wells and Coppersmith (1994) \(SRL ~ \mathbf{M}\) scaling relationships for all and Strike-slip events. WY15 OLS and WY15 Deming correspond to the Wells and Youngs (2015) \(SRL ~ \mathbf{M}\) scaling relationships using ordinary-least-squares and errors-in-variables regression models. L10 DS, L10 SS, and L10 SRC correspond to the Leonard (2010) \(SRL ~ \mathbf{M}\) scaling relationships for Dip-slip, Strike-slip, and Stable-Continental events. The proposed model is in agreement with the existing model over different magnitude ranges. It is in good agreement with the Leonard (2010) scaling relationship for small to moderate size events, and in good agreement with the Wells and Coppersmith (1994) and Wells and Youngs (2015) scaling relationships at large size events. A potential reason for the agreement at different magnitude ranges is that the dataset used by Leonard (2010) was primarily composed of events ranging from \(\mathbf{M}~5\) to \(7\), while datasets used by Wells and Coppersmith (1994) and Wells and Youngs (2015) was primarily composed of events ranging from \(\mathbf{M}~6\) to \(7.8\).

Figure 14. Comparison Preferred Model (Model 1, D~sqrt(A)) with existing SLR relationships
